StratMem Agent: Information-Theoretic Strategy Memory with Failure-Aware Compression, Hybrid Cognitive Retrieval, and PAC-Bayes Certified Test-Time Evolution

Author: Ouadi Maakoul

Abstract

Contemporary agentic large language model (LLM) systems suffer from attention dilution and reasoning brittleness due to reliance on content-heavy memory mechanisms such as Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) and long-context windows. While recent frameworks like Memory Intelligence Agent (MIA) have demonstrated the empirical promise of strategy memory—storing compressed workflows rather than raw content—existing approaches lack theoretical grounding, stable retrieval structures, and formal guarantees against policy collapse during self-evolution. This paper introduces StratMem Agent, a theoretically grounded and computationally lightweight architecture that synthesizes state-of-the-art advances in information theory, hybrid retrieval, and test-time optimization.

StratMem replaces heuristic trajectory storage with five core innovations: (i) a failure-aware Information Bottleneck (IB) variational compressor that preserves both success workflows and high-surprise failure constraints, supported by a novel PAC-Bayes generalization bound with effective sample weighting; (ii) a Hybrid Cognitive Retriever that fuses semantic, topological (Graph-of-Trajectories), temporal, and activation-based retrieval pathways; (iii) an entropy-regularized multi-reviewer ensemble augmented with lightweight sheaf-theoretic contradiction detection; (iv) a Memory-Aware Test-Time Scaling (MaTTS) loop with frozen Test-Time Preference Optimization (TPO) implemented via evolutionary strategies over LoRA adapters; and (v) explicit memory management primitives governed by a Fisher-Rao/Bhattacharyya augmented PAC-Bayes drift certificate.

We formalize the Memory Efficiency Ratio (MER) to quantify the advantage of strategy memory over content memory and derive a CLUB-based concentration bound for reliable mutual information estimation. Through rigorous theoretical analysis and a comprehensive experimental protocol, we demonstrate that a 7B–13B multimodal Executor equipped with StratMem is provably capable of monotonic improvement over long inference horizons without catastrophic forgetting or reward hacking. The work delivers a mathematically verifiable framework for agentic memory and an open-source implementation, advancing the field from empirical engineering toward principled, certifiable AI research assistants.

