1. Introduction

The rapid maturation of LLM-based autonomous agents has exposed a fundamental architectural bottleneck: memory. Agents tasked with deep research, multi-step reasoning, or complex tool orchestration must retain and recall vast amounts of contextual information—documents, code outputs, search results, and intermediate reasoning chains. The dominant paradigms for agent memory are variants of content-heavy storage: Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) injects raw text chunks into the prompt; long-context windows (now exceeding 1M tokens) preserve the entire conversation history; and episodic buffers cache full trajectories with heuristic summarization.

While these methods provide a naive form of recall, they all suffer from attention dilution. As the task horizon lengthens, the Executor LLM must sift through a growing sea of potentially irrelevant information, increasing the signal-to-noise ratio of the working context. This leads to empirically observed phenomena: tool misdirection, factual hallucination induced by distractor context, and reasoning brittleness where the agent loses the "plot" of the task.

1.1 The Promise of Strategy Memory

A compelling alternative has emerged in the form of process memory or strategy memory. Rather than storing what the agent saw, strategy memory stores how the agent succeeded (or failed) in analogous past situations. The Memory Intelligence Agent (MIA) framework (ECNU-SII, 2026) provided the first large-scale empirical validation of this paradigm. By maintaining a memory bank of compressed trajectories and retrieving them based on workflow similarity, MIA equipped with a 7B Executor matched or exceeded the performance of closed 30B+ models using content-heavy memory alone on benchmarks like GAIA and HotpotQA.

Despite this empirical breakthrough, MIA's design left several critical gaps that recent research has only begun to address. MIA employs heuristic summarization without formal justification; it stores trajectories in a flat vector database, ignoring the rich graph structure of workflows; it fails to systematically exploit informative failures; and its periodic QLoRA updates risk reward hacking and catastrophic policy drift.

Recent parallel advances—including ReasoningBank (Google Research, 2025), MemFly (arXiv, 2026), SuperLocalMemory V3 (Zenodo, 2026), SYNAPSE (2025), and Test-Time Preference Optimization (ICML 2025)—have each contributed a piece of the solution. ReasoningBank demonstrates that distilling "negative constraints" from failures prevents repeated mistakes. MemFly grounds memory evolution in the Information Bottleneck (IB) principle but does not explicitly weight failure trajectories. SuperLocalMemory V3 introduces sheaf cohomology for formal contradiction detection and information-geometric lifecycle management. SYNAPSE and MAGMA show that hybrid retrieval fusing multiple structural views outperforms flat semantic search. TPO demonstrates that a frozen LLM can be aligned with preferences during inference without backpropagation.

StratMem Agent is a unified architecture that synthesizes these isolated advances into a single, theoretically grounded framework. Our central thesis is that strategy memory is an instantiation of the Information Bottleneck principle, but one that must be augmented with failure-awareness, multi-pathway retrieval, explicit management primitives, and certified test-time scaling to be robust and verifiable.

1.2 Contributions

This work makes the following novel contributions, bridging the gap between empirical heuristics and provable agent design:

1. Failure-Aware IB-Optimal Compression (C1): We replace heuristic summarization with a variational IB encoder trained on a weighted objective. We define a weight function $w(\tau) = 1 + \alpha \cdot \mathbb{1}_{\text{fail}}(\tau) \cdot \text{Surprise}(\tau)$ that prioritizes informative failures. We prove a Failure-Aware PAC-IB Generalization Bound (Proposition A.1) showing that this weighting increases the effective sample size $n_{\text{eff}}$ in high-uncertainty regions, tightening the generalization gap precisely where heuristic baselines collapse.
2. Hybrid Cognitive Retrieval (C2): We model trajectories as a Graph-of-Trajectories (GoT) and retrieve using a dynamic, query-adaptive ensemble of four pathways: semantic GNN embeddings, topological policy-guided traversal, temporal pattern matching, and activation-based entity spreading. This hybrid design is validated by recent findings in SYNAPSE and ACGM.
3. Entropy-Regularized Multi-Reviewer Consensus with Sheaf-Theoretic Contradiction Detection (C3): We formalize unsupervised trajectory scoring via an ensemble with entropy regularization to maintain diversity. We further integrate a lightweight cellular sheaf model (validated by SuperLocalMemory V3) to detect irreconcilable contradictions in reviewer feedback. A Nyström approximation (Proposition A.4) ensures this check remains computationally feasible for real-time use.
4. Memory-Aware Test-Time Scaling with Gradient-Free TPO (C4): We replace periodic fine-tuning with a MaTTS loop. When confidence is low, the agent generates diverse rollouts, selects the best via reviewer consensus, and distills the winning strategy into memory. Policy updates are performed via evolutionary strategies (ES) over LoRA adapters with a DPO objective, keeping the base model frozen and satisfying test-time compute constraints (Section A.6).
5. Fisher-Rao/Bhattacharyya Augmented PAC-Bayes Drift Certificate (C5): We define a composite drift metric combining KL divergence and the Bhattacharyya distance (the geodesic on the probability simplex). We prove an exponential tail bound (Proposition A.3) on policy drift, providing a rigorous, computationally light trigger for automatic rollback to safe checkpoints, thereby guaranteeing stability during lifelong self-evolution.
6. Memory Efficiency Ratio (MER) Formalization: We define MER as the ratio of mutual information $I(Z_{\text{strat}}; Y)$ to $I(Z_{\text{content}}; Y)$ under constant compression budget, and provide a CLUB-based concentration bound (Proposition A.2) to reliably estimate this metric from finite samples.

1.3 Research Questions

This work is structured around five core research questions:

· RQ1 (Compression): Does failure-aware IB compression provably bound noise reduction and yield MER > 1.6 on multi-step reasoning tasks?
· RQ2 (Judgment): Can the entropy-regularized ensemble with sheaf-theoretic checks maintain robust, label-free judgment without consensus collapse?
· RQ3 (Retrieval): Does the hybrid cognitive retriever (GoT + four pathways) improve recall@3 and downstream success over flat baselines?
· RQ4 (Evolution): Does the MaTTS + frozen TPO loop yield monotonic accuracy improvement over inference epochs with certified drift bounds, outperforming QLoRA baselines?
· RQ5 (Management): Do explicit primitives (Consolidate, Forget, Update) reduce memory footprint and improve retrieval latency over implicit decay?

1.4 Scope and Assumptions

StratMem is designed for lightweight, open-source Executors (7B–13B parameters) with standard tools (web search, Python sandbox, file I/O). We make explicit assumptions that are empirically validated: reviewer accuracy $p \geq 0.7$, bounded mutual information estimation variance via CLUB, and that the TPO-ES update cost is amortized over long-horizon tasks. The work is accompanied by a full open-source implementation and a roadmap for target publications.

By shifting the paradigm from "storing more content" to "compressing better, failure-aware strategies," StratMem Agent establishes a rigorous, verifiable foundation for the next generation of efficient and trustworthy AI research assistants.

The StratMem Agent framework is well-grounded in recent advances. Below is a detailed, publication-ready draft of Chapters 2 and 3, incorporating the latest research and the rigorous mathematical foundation.

