Chapter 2: Related Work

The rapid evolution of autonomous LLM-based agents has driven a corresponding surge in research on agent memory systems. This chapter positions StratMem Agent within the broader research landscape, examining five interconnected threads of recent work: (1) taxonomies and diagnostic frameworks for agent memory; (2) process- and strategy-oriented memory architectures; (3) information-theoretic and geometric foundations for memory compression; (4) hybrid and graph-structured retrieval mechanisms; and (5) test-time alignment and self-evolution frameworks. We highlight how StratMem synthesizes and extends these advances.

2.1 Taxonomies and Diagnostic Frameworks for Agent Memory

Before designing new memory architectures, it is essential to understand the functional space of existing systems. Several comprehensive surveys now provide this necessary framing. A recent survey published in late 2025 formalizes agent memory as a “write–manage–read loop” and provides a unified view of memory mechanisms spanning temporal scope, representational substrate, and control policy, covering work from 2022 through early 2026. Another survey released in early 2026 provides a three-dimensional taxonomy along memory substrate (internal vs. external), cognitive mechanism (episodic, semantic, sensory, working, procedural), and memory subject (agent- and user-centric).

These surveys highlight a critical insight: the dominant paradigms for agent memory—Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG), long-context windows, and heuristic summarization—suffer from a fundamental tension between capacity and precision. The diagnostic framework of Zhang et al. (2026) makes this tension explicit by analyzing how performance differences manifest across write strategies (raw chunks, Mem0-style fact extraction, MemGPT-style summarization) and retrieval methods (cosine, BM25, hybrid reranking), revealing that retrieval quality often degrades as memory banks grow, a phenomenon we term attention dilution. StratMem directly addresses this bottleneck by compressing strategy-relevant information rather than storing content, thereby maintaining a high signal-to-noise ratio even as the memory bank scales.

2.2 Process and Strategy Memory: From MIA to ReasoningBank

The most direct precursor to StratMem is the Memory Intelligence Agent (MIA) framework (ECNU-SII, 2026). MIA introduced a Manager-Planner-Executor architecture with a non-parametric memory system that stores compressed historical search trajectories. On benchmarks like GAIA and HotpotQA, MIA equipped with a 7B Executor matched or exceeded closed 30B+ models using content-heavy memory alone. This empirical breakthrough validated the core intuition of strategy memory: storing how an agent succeeds is more valuable than storing what it sees.

However, MIA's design leaves several critical gaps. Its compression mechanism is heuristic rather than principled; it stores trajectories in a flat vector database, ignoring the rich graph structure of workflows; it fails to systematically exploit informative failures; and its periodic QLoRA updates risk reward hacking and catastrophic policy drift.

ReasoningBank (Google Research, September 2025) addresses the failure-utilization gap directly. ReasoningBank is a memory framework that enables AI agents to learn from both successful and failed experiences, extracting generalizable reasoning strategies that improve performance over time. Crucially, ReasoningBank stores not only success patterns but also negative constraints distilled from failures, turning every interaction—successful or failed—into structured, reusable memory. This work provides strong empirical evidence that failure-awareness is a critical component of effective strategy memory, motivating StratMem's failure-aware Information Bottleneck (IB) compressor (C1).

2.3 Information-Theoretic and Geometric Foundations for Memory

While MIA and ReasoningBank provide empirical advances, recent work has sought to ground agent memory in rigorous mathematical principles. MemFly (HKUST and Nanjing University, February 2026) is the first framework to ground memory evolution in the Information Bottleneck (IB) principle, minimizing compression entropy while maximizing relevance entropy via a gradient-free optimizer, and constructing a stratified memory structure for efficient storage. MemFly's hybrid retrieval mechanism (semantic, symbolic, topological) further demonstrates the value of multi-pathway retrieval. However, MemFly does not explicitly weight failure trajectories, nor does it provide formal generalization bounds.

SuperLocalMemory V3 (March 2026) pushes the mathematical foundation further by establishing the first information-geometric, sheaf-theoretic, and stochastic-dynamical foundations for AI agent memory systems. The paper replaces heuristic similarity with a Fisher-Rao metric (Riemannian distance on the statistical manifold) and detects contradictions across memory contexts via sheaf cohomology, where non-trivial first cohomology classes correspond precisely to irreconcilable inconsistencies—the first algebraic consistency guarantee for agent memory. StratMem integrates this sheaf-theoretic contradiction detection as a lightweight consistency check (C3) and uses the Fisher-Rao/Bhattacharyya metric for drift monitoring (C5).

Other notable works include Lightweight LLM Agent Memory with Small Language Models (April 2026), which proposes LightMem, a modular memory system driven by Small Language Models (SLMs) for better memory retrieval, and D-MEM (March 2026), a biologically inspired architecture that decouples short-term interaction from long-term cognitive restructuring via dopamine-gated routing.

2.4 Hybrid and Graph-Structured Retrieval

The shift from flat vector search to structured, multi-pathway retrieval is a defining trend in recent agent memory research. SYNAPSE implements a Triple Hybrid Retrieval strategy that fuses geometric embeddings with activation-based graph traversal, significantly outperforming state-of-the-art methods in complex temporal and multi-hop reasoning tasks. Think-on-Graph 3.0 (ToG-3, 2026) introduces a Multi-Agent Context Evolution and Retrieval (MACER) mechanism that dynamically builds a targeted graph index tailored to the query, enabling precise evidence retrieval even with lightweight LLMs.

Look Back to Reason Forward: Revisitable Memory for Long-Context LLM Agents (February 2026) presents ReMemR1, which integrates the mechanism of memory retrieval into the memory update process, enabling the agent to selectively callback historical memories for non-linear reasoning. These works collectively demonstrate that hybrid retrieval—fusing semantic, topological, temporal, and activation-based pathways—yields superior performance over flat baselines. StratMem's Hybrid Cognitive Retriever (C2) synthesizes these advances into a query-adaptive four-pathway ensemble.

2.5 Test-Time Alignment and Self-Evolution

A major challenge in lifelong agent learning is balancing improvement with stability. Traditional fine-tuning approaches (e.g., QLoRA in MIA) risk catastrophic forgetting and reward hacking. Recent work has explored test-time alignment as a safer alternative.

Test-Time Preference Optimization (TPO) (ICML 2025) demonstrates that a frozen LLM can be aligned with human preferences during inference using iterative textual feedback, removing the need to update model parameters. LLMdoctor (January 2026) extends this paradigm with a patient-doctor framework that steers a large, frozen patient LLM with a smaller, specialized doctor model via token-level flow-guided preference optimization (TFPO).

StratMem's self-evolution engine combines Memory-Aware Test-Time Scaling (MaTTS) from ReasoningBank with a gradient-free, evolutionary-strategies implementation of TPO over LoRA adapters (C4). This approach keeps the base model frozen, ensuring zero-gradient adaptation, while still allowing the agent to distill winning strategies from parallel rollouts into memory. The PAC-Bayes drift certificate (C5) provides a formal guarantee that policy updates remain within safe bounds.

2.6 Multi-Agent Consensus and Drift Control

Ensuring robust, label-free judgment of trajectory quality is essential for self-evolution. MARS (Multi-Agent Review System) uses role-based independent review, while recent work on Multi-Agent Debate with Adaptive Stability Detection uses Beta-Binomial mixture models to track judge consensus. StratMem augments this with entropy regularization to maintain reviewer diversity and sheaf-theoretic contradiction detection for formal consistency guarantees.

For drift control, EPIC (AISTATS 2025) provides PAC-Bayes guarantees for lifelong RL, and Deep Actor-Critics with Tight Risk Certificates (2025) generates PAC-Bayes risk certificates for trustworthy decision-making. StratMem's Fisher-Rao/Bhattacharyya augmented PAC-Bayes bound (Proposition 3.5 in the original proposal) builds on this foundation to provide tighter concentration guarantees, enabling automatic rollback to safe checkpoints when drift exceeds a certified threshold.

