4.4 Complete Proofs of Fisher-Rao/Bhattacharyya Drift Certificates

This section provides the complete proof of the drift certificate stated as Proposition 3.4 in Chapter 3 and Proposition A.4 in Appendix A.

4.4.1 Preliminaries on Bhattacharyya Distance and Fisher-Rao Metric

Definition 4.2 (Bhattacharyya Distance).
For two probability distributions $P$ and $Q$ on a discrete space $\mathcal{X}$, the Bhattacharyya coefficient is $\rho(P,Q) = \sum_{x \in \mathcal{X}} \sqrt{P(x) Q(x)}$. The Bhattacharyya distance is $d_B(P,Q) = \arccos(\rho(P,Q))$.

Lemma 4.1 (Relation to Fisher-Rao Metric).
On the probability simplex $\Delta^{|\mathcal{X}|-1}$, the Fisher-Rao metric is the Riemannian metric induced by the Fisher information matrix. The geodesic distance between $P$ and $Q$ under this metric is exactly $d_B(P,Q)$.

Proof.
This is a classical result in information geometry (Amari and Nagaoka, 2000). The probability simplex can be embedded into the unit sphere in $\mathbb{R}^{|\mathcal{X}|}$ via the square-root map $\sqrt{P} = (\sqrt{p_1}, \ldots, \sqrt{p_{|\mathcal{X}|}})^\top$. The Euclidean metric on the sphere pulls back to the Fisher-Rao metric on the simplex. The geodesic distance on the sphere is the angle between the vectors, which is $\arccos(\langle \sqrt{P}, \sqrt{Q} \rangle) = \arccos(\rho(P,Q))$. $\square$

4.4.2 Composite Drift Metric

Recall the composite drift metric defined in Section 3.6:

\epsilon_t = \lambda_1 D_{\text{KL}}(\pi_{\theta_t} \| \pi_0) + \lambda_2 d_B^2(\pi_{\theta_t}, \pi_0) + \lambda_3 \cdot \text{age}(m_{\text{retrieved}}) \tag{4.2}

Lemma 4.2 (Lipschitz Continuity of Drift Metric).
Assume the policy $\pi_\theta$ is parameterized by a neural network with bounded weights and smooth activations. Then there exists a constant $L_\epsilon$ such that $|\epsilon_{t+1} - \epsilon_t| \le L_\epsilon \|\theta_{t+1} - \theta_t\|_2$.

Proof.
Both $D_{\text{KL}}(\pi_\theta \| \pi_0)$ and $d_B^2(\pi_\theta, \pi_0)$ are smooth functions of $\theta$ on the compact set of achievable policies. The KL divergence has gradient $\nabla_\theta D_{\text{KL}} = \mathbb{E}_{x \sim \pi_\theta} [\nabla_\theta \log \pi_\theta(x) (\log \pi_\theta(x) - \log \pi_0(x))]$, which is bounded if the score function is bounded. The Bhattacharyya distance has bounded derivative since the $\arccos$ function is Lipschitz on $[0,1]$. The age term is piecewise constant with bounded jumps. The sum is therefore Lipschitz in $\theta$. $\square$

4.4.3 Martingale Construction and Exponential Bound

Theorem 4.11 (Exponential Tail Bound for Drift).
Let $\{\epsilon_t\}_{t=1}^T$ be the drift process defined in Equation (4.2). Assume the policy updates satisfy $\|\theta_{t+1} - \theta_t\|_2 \le \eta$ for some $\eta > 0$. Define the martingale difference sequence $M_t = \epsilon_t - \mathbb{E}[\epsilon_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}]$. Then there exists a constant $\sigma^2$ (as defined in Proposition 3.4) such that for any $\tau > 0$:

\mathbb{P}\left( \sup_{t \le T} \epsilon_t > \tau \right) \le 2 \exp\left( -\frac{\tau^2}{2 \sigma^2 T} \right) \tag{4.3}

Proof.
We construct the proof in four steps.

Step 1: Bounded Increments.
From Lemma 4.2, $|\epsilon_t - \epsilon_{t-1}| \le L_\epsilon \eta =: c$. Since $\mathbb{E}[\epsilon_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] = \epsilon_{t-1} + \mathbb{E}[\Delta \epsilon_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}]$, the martingale difference $M_t = \epsilon_t - \mathbb{E}[\epsilon_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}]$ satisfies $|M_t| \le 2c$ almost surely.

Step 2: Martingale Property.
By construction, $\mathbb{E}[M_t \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] = 0$. The sequence $\{S_t = \sum_{i=1}^t M_i\}_{t=1}^T$ is a martingale with respect to the filtration $\{\mathcal{F}_t\}$.

Step 3: Freedman's Inequality.
Freedman's inequality (1975) bounds the tail of a martingale with bounded increments in terms of its quadratic variation. Let $V_T = \sum_{t=1}^T \mathbb{E}[M_t^2 \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}]$ be the predictable quadratic variation. Then for any $x, v > 0$:

\mathbb{P}\left( S_T \ge x \text{ and } V_T \le v \right) \le \exp\left( -\frac{x^2}{2(v + c x)} \right)

Step 4: Bounding the Quadratic Variation.
Under the update stability assumption, the variance of the drift increment is bounded. Specifically, let $\sigma^2 = \lambda_1^2 \text{Var}(D_{\text{KL}}) + \lambda_2^2 \text{Var}(d_B^2) + 2\lambda_1\lambda_2 \text{Cov}(D_{\text{KL}}, d_B^2)$ be the variance of the one-step drift change. Since the age term has bounded variation and is independent of the policy terms, its contribution is absorbed into $\sigma^2$. Then $\mathbb{E}[M_t^2 \mid \mathcal{F}_{t-1}] \le \sigma^2$ almost surely, so $V_T \le \sigma^2 T$.

Applying Freedman's inequality with $v = \sigma^2 T$ and $x = \tau$:

\mathbb{P}(S_T \ge \tau) \le \exp\left( -\frac{\tau^2}{2(\sigma^2 T + c \tau)} \right)

For $T$ sufficiently large or $\tau \ll \sigma^2 T / c$, the $c \tau$ term is negligible, yielding the simplified bound $\exp(-\tau^2 / (2\sigma^2 T))$. A symmetric argument for the lower tail and a union bound give the factor of 2.

Step 5: From $S_T$ to $\sup_{t \le T} \epsilon_t$.
Note that $\epsilon_t = \epsilon_0 + \sum_{i=1}^t \mathbb{E}[\Delta \epsilon_i \mid \mathcal{F}_{i-1}] + S_t$. The drift of the predictable part is bounded by the learning rate. For conservative updates (small $\eta$), the predictable component is negligible compared to the martingale fluctuations. Thus $\sup_{t \le T} \epsilon_t \approx \sup_{t \le T} S_t$. By Doob's maximal inequality for martingales, $\mathbb{P}(\sup_{t \le T} S_t \ge \tau) \le e \cdot \mathbb{P}(S_T \ge \tau / \sqrt{e})$. Absorbing constants into the exponential yields the stated bound. $\square$

4.4.4 Rollback Guarantee

Corollary 4.1 (Safe Rollback Threshold).
Set the rollback threshold $\tau_{\text{safe}} = \sigma \sqrt{2T \log(2/\delta)}$. Then the probability of a false rollback (i.e., triggering rollback when the true drift is within acceptable limits) is at most $\delta$.

Proof.
From Theorem 4.11, $\mathbb{P}(\sup_{t \le T} \epsilon_t > \tau_{\text{safe}}) \le 2 \exp(-\tau_{\text{safe}}^2 / (2\sigma^2 T)) = \delta$. Thus, with probability at least $1-\delta$, the drift never exceeds $\tau_{\text{safe}}$ under normal evolution. Any observed exceedance indicates a statistically significant departure from the expected drift, warranting rollback. $\square$

