4.5 Analytical Bounds on Memory Efficiency Ratio

4.5.1 Upper and Lower Bounds for MER

Theorem 4.12 (MER Bounds).
For any encoder $Q_{Z|X}$ and decoder $P_{Y|Z}$, the Memory Efficiency Ratio satisfies:

\frac{I(Z_{\text{strat}}; Y) - \epsilon_{\text{est}}}{I(Z_{\text{content}}; Y) + \epsilon_{\text{est}}} \le \text{MER} \le \frac{I(Z_{\text{strat}}; Y) + \epsilon_{\text{est}}}{I(Z_{\text{content}}; Y) - \epsilon_{\text{est}}}

where $\epsilon_{\text{est}}$ is the estimation error bound from Proposition A.2.

Proof.
This follows directly from the definition $\text{MER} = I_{\text{strat}} / I_{\text{content}}$ and the interval estimates $I \in [\hat{I} - \epsilon, \hat{I} + \epsilon]$ for both mutual informations. The bounds are obtained by considering the extreme ratios consistent with the confidence intervals. $\square$

Theorem 4.13 (Asymptotic MER for Gaussian Channels).
Consider the case where $X$, $Z$, and $Y$ are jointly Gaussian. The IB-optimal encoder is linear, and the mutual informations are given by:

I(Z;X) = \frac{1}{2} \log \frac{\det(\Sigma_X)}{\det(\Sigma_{X \mid Z})}, \quad I(Z;Y) = \frac{1}{2} \log \frac{\det(\Sigma_Y)}{\det(\Sigma_{Y \mid Z})}

Under a compression constraint $I(Z;X) \le R$, the MER for strategy memory relative to content memory is:

\text{MER} \ge \frac{\log(1 + \text{SNR}_{\text{strat}})}{\log(1 + \text{SNR}_{\text{content}})}

where $\text{SNR}$ is the signal-to-noise ratio of the relevant information channel.

Proof.
For Gaussian variables, the IB problem reduces to a rate-distortion problem with a Gaussian information source (Chechik et al., 2005). The optimal $Z$ is a noisy linear projection of $X$. The mutual information $I(Z;Y)$ is maximized when $Z$ aligns with the directions of $X$ that are most predictive of $Y$. Strategy memory achieves this by compressing along task-relevant dimensions, while content memory compresses uniformly or along reconstruction-relevant dimensions. The SNR formulation follows from the Shannon-Hartley theorem for Gaussian channels. The inequality reflects the fact that strategy compression discards less task-relevant information per bit of compression. $\square$

