Appendix G: Additional Lemmas and Technical Results

G.1 Hoeffding's Inequality for Weighted Sums

Lemma G.1 (Weighted Hoeffding).
Let $X_1, \ldots, X_n$ be independent random variables with $X_i \in [a_i, b_i]$. Let $w_1, \ldots, w_n$ be non-negative weights with $W = \sum w_i$. Then for any $t > 0$:

\mathbb{P}\left( \sum_{i=1}^n w_i X_i - \mathbb{E}\left[\sum w_i X_i\right] \ge t \right) \le \exp\left( -\frac{2t^2}{\sum w_i^2 (b_i - a_i)^2} \right)

This justifies the effective sample size $n_{\text{eff}} = \frac{(\sum w_i)^2}{\sum w_i^2}$ when $b_i - a_i$ is constant.

G.2 Data Processing Inequality for Weighted IB

Lemma G.2 (Weighted Data Processing).
For any Markov chain $X \to Z \to Y$ and non-negative weight function $w(X)$ bounded above by $W_{\max}$:

I_w(Z;Y) \le I_w(X;Y)

where $I_w$ is the weighted mutual information $I_w(A;B) = \mathbb{E}_{P_A}[w(A) D_{\text{KL}}(P_{B|A} \| P_B)]$.

Proof.
By the standard data processing inequality, $I(X;Y \mid Z=z) \le I(X;Y)$ for each $z$. Weighting by $w(X)$ and taking expectation preserves the inequality because $w(X) \ge 0$. $\square$

G.3 Lipschitz Continuity of GNN Embeddings

Lemma G.3.
Let $\phi$ be a Graph Neural Network with $L$ layers, each using a Lipschitz activation function (e.g., ReLU, tanh) with constant $L_\sigma$, and weight matrices with spectral norm bounded by $C_W$. Then $\phi$ is Lipschitz with respect to the graph edit distance (GED) metric on graphs:

\|\phi(G_1) - \phi(G_2)\|_2 \le L_\phi \cdot \text{GED}(G_1, G_2)

where $L_\phi = (C_W L_\sigma)^L \cdot \sqrt{d_{\text{out}}}$.

Proof Sketch.
Each graph edit operation (node/edge addition/deletion) changes the input features by a bounded amount. The GNN is a composition of Lipschitz operations (graph convolution, activation, pooling). The Lipschitz constant composes across layers. $\square$

G.4 Ebbinghaus Forgetting Curve Formulation

The utility of a memory entry decays according to:

U(t) = U_0 \cdot e^{-\lambda t} + \gamma \cdot \text{retrieval\_count}(t)

where $t$ is the time since last access, $\lambda$ is the decay rate, and $\gamma$ is the boost per retrieval. Memories with $U(t) < \tau_{\text{forget}}$ are pruned. This implements adaptive forgetting based on the spacing effect from cognitive psychology.

